Category:
Analysis & Reporting (Banking & Financial Services)
Other (Education & Training)
Ad Text:
Employment Type: Full-time
Duration: Continuing
Remuneration: $127,351 - $143,488 +17% super + leave loading (commensurate with experience)
Location: UNSW Kensington Campus (Hybrid Working Opportunities)

About UNSW:
UNSW isn’t like other places you’ve worked. Yes, we’re a large organisation with a diverse and talented community, a community doing extraordinary things. Together, we are driven to be thoughtful, practical, and purposeful in all we do. Taking this combined approach is what makes our work matter. If you want a career where you can thrive, be challenged and do meaningful work, you’re in the right place.

Why Your Role Matters:
The Group Consolidation & Reporting Analyst provides complex financial services aligned with the University’s Financial Management framework and supports primarily a portfolio which includes Central BAU and UNSW’s controlled entities. The position plays a key role in the management of reporting and analysis, forecasting and controlling to enable tracking of revenues, expenditures and monitoring financial performance across designated business units.

The work is time sensitive and reporting deadlines closely adhered to in ensuring FP&A leads have clarity of the results and performance of business units looked after.

This position reports to the Senior Manager Group Management Reporting and has no direct reports.

Responsibilities Summary:

Prepare, review and analyse financial reports for Central BAU. When required, work with relevant Finance and Human Resources staff to correct omissions and inaccuracies.
Collaborate with Finance Business Partners and Human Resources to record, forecast and analyse  centrally funded severance and redundancies and Parental Leave.
Review and manage accuracy and integrity of Central BAU data. Investigate variances to budget and forecasts to ensure all issues are identified and managed in a timely manner.
Prepare and post ad hoc journals and prepare ad hoc analysis and data as required.
Maintain a three-year rolling forecast for Central BAU.
Manage the reporting cycle and scope of deliveries (month-end, quarterly and year-end) for the main Controlled Entities. Load forecast data in Calumo. Check and review returned packs to make them ready for distribution to Senior Management.
Collaborate with other departments, including Financial Control & Compliance, Treasury, Finance Systems, Finance Business Partners’ teams, Human Resources and Controlled Entities, to facilitate the flow of information needed for accounting, reporting and forecasting.
Maintain accurate and comprehensive financial records, ensuring documentation is organised and accessible for audits and reporting purposes.
Maintain the strictest level of confidentiality of sensitive information.

For more information regarding the responsibilities for this role, please refer to the Position Description at JOBS@UNSW.

Skills and Experience Summary:

Relevant tertiary qualification with (or working towards) a CA or CPA qualification (or equivalent) combined with experience in analysis and reporting.
Substantial experience of accounting standards relevant to Central BAU and Controlled Entities’ transactions.
Demonstrable self-motivation and personal drive to succeed combined with intellectual curiosity and a drive for continuous improvement.
Demonstrated ability to work both independently and collaboratively in a fast-paced, complex environment.
A proven background in accurate budget preparation and monitoring, financial analysis, forecasting and management reporting in a multi-faceted, large and complex environment.
Demonstrated critical thinking and ability to analyse, interpret and integrate complex data and provide analysis to FP&A leads.
Sound knowledge of computer applications, reporting tools, and particularly a high level of proficiency in Microsoft Excel.



Benefits and Culture: People are at the core of everything we do. We recognise it is the contributions of our staff who make UNSW one of the best universities in Australia and the world. Our benefits include: 

Career development opportunities 
17% Superannuation contributions and additional leave loading payments 
Additional 3 days of leave over Christmas period 
Discounts and entitlements (retail, education, fitness)

How to Apply: Make each day matter with a meaningful career at UNSW. Submit your CV along with a cover letter that addresses your suitability for the position in relation to the selection criteria (listed in the ‘Skills & Experience’ section of the PD) via the application portal.

Applications close: 11:30pm on January 16th, 2026.

A copy of the Position Description can be found on JOBS@UNSW.

Get in Touch: For queries regarding the recruitment process, contact Lucy Gerondis, Talent Acquisition Consultant, UNSW: l.gerondis@unsw.edu.au

Applications sent via email will not be accepted, please apply via the application portal.

UNSW is committed to evolving a culture that embraces equity and supports a diverse and inclusive community where everyone can participate fairly, in a safe and respectful environment. We welcome candidates from all backgrounds and encourage applications from people of diverse gender, sexual orientation, cultural and linguistic backgrounds, Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander background, people with disability and those with caring and family responsibilities. UNSW provides workplace adjustments for people with disability, and access to flexible work options for eligible staff.

The University reserves the right not to proceed with any appointment.

Job Title: Data & Testing Lead - Donesafe Implementation / Digital Transformation
Ad Text:
Contract: 6 Months (High potential for extension)  

About Stowe Australia 

Stowe Australia is a leading family owned electrical and communications contractor with a heritage dating back to 1910. As one of Australia's largest electrical contractors with a national footprint and a workforce of over 2,000 employees, the company delivers comprehensive solutions across major projects. Driven by a strong safety culture and a commitment to innovation, Stowe combines over a century of operational excellence with a steady and diverse client base throughout the country. 

The Opportunity 

Stowe Australia is embarking on a major national transformation of our Health, Safety, Environment, and Quality (HSEQ) systems. We are moving away from legacy processes to implement the HSI Donesafe platform across our entire national operation.  To support this program, we’re seeking an experienced Data Analysis & Testing Lead. 

This is a core assurance and is essential to the successful delivery of the program.  This role will own the data quality, extraction, cleansing, validation and end to end UAT making this role a key determinant of whether the platform is safe, accurate, and ready for national deployment.   

This is a hands-on, high-impact contract role where you will work directly with the project team, SMEs, and the vendor to ensure the platform is ready for a successful national rollout. 

The Role 

As the Data & Testing Lead, you will be responsible for: 

Leading data mapping, cleansing, transformation, migration and validation activities 
Developing and implementing end-to-end testing strategies, comprehensive test plans, detailed scripts, and UAT governance  
Coordinating and executing UAT across 25+ Donesafe modules 
Managing defects, retesting and go-live readiness 
Working closely with the HSI Donesafe vendor team and Stowe SMEs 
Supporting documentation, reporting and change readiness activities 
You will be the key technical and Quality Assurance specialist for this transformation program. 

About You 

You are a detail-oriented data specialist with strong testing experience and the confidence to lead a large-scale SaaS implementation. You bring: 

Essential 

5+ years in data analysis, data migration or data governance 
Strong experience leading UAT and functional testing for SaaS/enterprise systems 
Ability to create clear test plans, test cases, scripts and traceability 
Excellent Excel capability (Power Query, XLOOKUP, cleansing, validation) 
Strong communication and stakeholder engagement skills 
Ability to work independently and proactively in a fast-paced delivery environment 

Nice to Have 

Experience with HSI Donesafe, HSI Solv, or other HSE/WHS systems (INX, Bsafe etc) 
Background in construction, electrical, mining, field services or compliance industries 
Experience with integrations (API/SFTP), SQL or Power BI 

Why Join This Project? 

Impact: Play a key role in a high profile digital transformation for an industry leader and deliver a platform that will enhance safety and operational excellence across the business 
Influence: You aren’t just inheriting a system; you are helping design it from the ground up to ensure it works for our people.  
Longevity: While this is a 6-month contract, extension is highly likely as we move into national rollout and continuous improvement phases. 

Ready to shape the future of safety at Stowe? 

If you are an experienced Data and Testing professional and wants to apply your skills to a major transformation project, apply now.

Job Title: Financial Planning & Analysis Manager - Corporate Services
Ad Text:
Are you an experienced FP&A Manager looking for your next exciting opportunity? Findex are currently looking for a Financial Planning & Analysis (FP&A) Manager - Corporate Services to join our Finance team! This is a permanent, full-time role, open to Melbourne or Sydney.

The FP&A Manager - Corporate Services is a commercial finance role reporting to the Senior FP&A Manager – Corporate Services. You will be responsible for preparing and communicating financial reporting and analysis for Corporate teams. You will be required to identify trends, prepare budgets and forecasts, build reports, and communicate actionable insights to key stakeholders in our business. 

Your role, your contribution!

Collaborating on the prompt delivery of accurate and complete forecasts for the Corporate Services division.
Provide timely management reporting to multiple Corporate and C-Suite stakeholders, and support with the preparation of Board and Executive Committee reporting packs
Consolidate divisional plans and prepare variance analyses, identifying trends, risks, and opportunities.
Support the development of the Corporate Services workforce plan including review and approval of new and replacement roles
Providing commercial and financial support to business stakeholders, presenting information in a way to facilitate and influence decision making to drive optimal business performance

The benefits of joining us!

Hybrid working environment that offers great flexibility, allowing you to work from home and office 
A true business partnering role that allows you to work with likeminded professionals and SMEs 
Engage with a culture that values continuous improvement and innovation

What you bring to the role:

Tertiary Qualification & CA or CPA qualified
Proven experience in financial analysis, planning, or business performance, ideally within professional services or a complex corporate environment.
Proven experience in budgeting, forecasting, and management reporting.
Strong commercial acumen and business partnering skills.
Experience coaching/mentoring junior staff
Proficient in Microsoft Excel + experience with PowerBI or similar data visualisation tools

If this role sounds like a good fit - Apply now!  

Our Impact: Why Findex?   

At Findex, we help clients manage, grow, and protect their financial future with confidence. Since 1987, we’ve become a leading Australasian provider of integrated accounting, advisory, and wealth solutions, delivered through our “Wealth Accountant” and Family Office models. With 2,500 professionals across 100+ offices, we combine local expertise with global reach and remain committed to supporting clients and communities in creating long-term financial security.

For the Community - The Findex Community Fund (FCF) is dedicated to giving back to the communities we serve. Since 2018, we have donated over $4.3 million to more than 800 charities across Australia and New Zealand. Collectively, our team has dedicated over 9,000 volunteer hours, making a tangible impact in their communities through personal engagement.  

For our Customers - Together, Findex and Crowe champion the success of over 75,000 Australasian businesses, helping them grow with expert advice, fresh thinking, and top-tier professional services. Here, you’re empowered to work in a way that brings out your best — supporting your growth, your team, and the clients who trust us to make a real difference  

For You - At Findex, we focus on developing our people first. With structured training and development opportunities, we allow our people to grow their career in a way that sets them up for success. We actively support our people by giving them extra support to external studies that is relevant to their role.   

For Diversity & Inclusion - Findex is an equal opportunity employer. We value diversity and are committed to creating an inclusive environment for all employees and encourage applications from candidates with a variety of strengths, backgrounds and experiences.

Job Title: Solution Delivery Analyst (Clinical) - multiple positions available
Category:
Business/Systems Analysts (Information & Communication Technology)
Government - State (Government & Defence)
Ad Text:
The role: 

Queensland Health recognises that progressing our digital health strategy is an essential part of our ongoing commitment to delivering safe, effective, and accessible healthcare to all Queenslanders.

Queensland Health is currently undertaking several of the largest health ICT programs and projects ever seen in Australia. The largest of these, the Digital Hospital Program (DHP) is a visionary program that continues to enable clinical services and enhance our technological capability by extending the availability of the ieMR into more hospitals and community care venues. The Digital Hospital Program will deliver advanced ieMR to 5 Metro North hospitals over the first 5 years. In parallel Queensland Health will be adding over 2,811 additional hospital beds across the state, with four entirely new hospitals and expansions to 11 already world-class facilities.

Implementing an integrated electronic Medical Record (ieMR) across all public hospitals in Queensland is at the heart of our digital transformation and is essential to delivering care, closer to home.  Already used in numerous facilities today, the ieMR is improving care and patient outcomes by offering Queensland Health clinicians access to real-time clinical information for their patients, at point of care.

A Solution Delivery Analyst (Clinical) plays a critical role in bridging clinical and business needs and IT solutions across eHealth Queensland, providing strategic advice on project direction, facilitate business requirements, use case development, and detailed engagement with clinical and business stakeholders. The role includes mentoring business analysts whilst ensuring effective communication and stakeholder engagement.

Is this opportunity for you?

To perform successfully in this role, you must demonstrate:

Proven experience working in a clinical digital transformation designing or redesigning workflows, processes in a healthcare system.
Ability to lead and manage multiple large stakeholder and clinical groups to achieve positive outcomes.
Proven experience in setting the direction for and leading business analysis activities, and in clinical digital transformation process redesign and business case development activities in the health care industry, and intimate knowledge of healthcare processes specifically those used for clinical digital transformation.
Experience overseeing, managing and defining business analysis and process modelling activities for large scale complex organisations.
Proven excellent negotiation, consultation, facilitation and effective written and oral communication skills for use in complex program/ project environment. 
Highly developed ability to manage staff and build client focused and effective teams providing high-quality services to clients

The following experience will be highly regarded:

Strong knowledge and prior experience working across ieMR in a clinical healthcare environment.

While experience in health care is not a mandatory requirement, we highly value candidates who have demonstrated relevant experience in clinical systems, health IT, or digital health. If your experience is in other sectors, please make sure to outline how your knowledge can transfer to the healthcare context.

To be considered for this exciting opportunity submit your CV or resume and a short statement (maximum 2 pages) addressing your experience in each of the key areas outlined above.

About eHealth Queensland:

eHealth Queensland is one of the largest Information Communication Technology operations in the state. It is responsible for ensuring the smooth operation of information systems and technologies so that Queensland Health employees and health providers have access to information that supports the delivery of health care.

Benefits of working with eHealth Queensland:

By joining eHealth Queensland you will work within a fast-paced, challenging and supportive environment where every employee plays a critical role in our ongoing success. 

You will enjoy a variety of benefits, including:

Competitive salary + generous superannuation and leave loading
Flexible working arrangements
Diverse work culture
Career training and development

To apply for this exciting opportunity, submit your resume and a short statement (maximum 2 pages) on how your experience, abilities, knowledge and personal qualities are relevant for the role, taking into account the key responsibilities and attributes noted in the ‘How you will be assessed' section of the role description.

Sydney CBD

Partner with stakeholders to embed data and AI ownership, governance practices  
Permanent Full-time Position, Sydney CBD location 
Hybrid working environment, attractive salary package 

About the Role 

In this role, you will establish, operate and advocate fit-for-purpose data and responsible AI frameworks, policies and best practices that enable effective and timely decisions on data and AI, aligned to legal, compliance, risk appetite and business value priorities  

Benefits 

A corporate wellbeing program with subsidised gym membership, free flu vaccinations and health check programs 
17.5% annual leave loading  
Comprehensive learning and development support aligned to icare’s Core Capabilities.  
Our People Awards - On-the-spot Recognition, Quarterly Values Awards & Our People Annual Awards 
Access to our Employee Assistance Program  

Duties 

It’s an exciting time at icare where no two days are the same; as a Manager, Data & AI Governance you will:

Work closely across whole of business, to establish and embed governance structures, data and AI ownership, and facilitate AI governance reviews ensuring they balance risk, value and compliance considerations and align with NSW Government frameworks and practices.  
Establish and embed data and AI risk management practices in partnership with Risk Management function, aligning with enterprise risk management frameworks and risk appetite.  
Design, embed and continuously adapt frameworks, policies and practices to cater for growing and innovative data, analytics and AI technologies and their usage in a changing legislative environment.  
Run and continuously improve the operation of Information and AI Governance Council and related groups, ensuring clear agendas, decisions actions, any escalations and accountabilities. Ensure relevant papers are drafted and submitted in a timely manner.  

 Skills & Experience  

Proven experience in establishing and operating data and AI governance in complex, regulated environments.  
Experience developing and maintaining data and AI governance frameworks, policies and artefacts and integrating them in business operations.  
Proven ability to gain endorsements and lead forums with senior stakeholders.  
Experience in guiding analytics, data science or AI teams on governance matters.  
Strong understanding of data management frameworks and practices (e.g. DMBOK, CPG 235) and ethical and responsible AI frameworks and emerging standards.  
Strong understanding of privacy, security and regulatory obligations related to data and AI.  

Culture  

We know our strength comes from the diversity of our people and would encourage people with different experiences and backgrounds to apply.   We are committed to our people’s development so the people of NSW can thrive. 

About the Company 

We care for the people of NSW, building confidence and trust so our communities can thrive. We make the complex simple, so our schemes deliver better outcomes for people and communities. Whether a person is severely injured in the workplace or on our roads, icare supports their long-term care needs to improve quality of life, including helping people return to work.  

For more information about icare visit our website 
icare operates a direct sourcing model so no agency introductions will be accepted 
We are a Circle Back Initiative Employer – we commit to respond to every applicant 
A talent pool may be created through this recruitment process.  

Please note that you must be an Australian citizen, permanent resident of Australia, New Zealand citizen with a current New Zealand passport or have unrestricted working rights to apply for this role.
